{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516238"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:40:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.72,0.11,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114383"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5083"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1816"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"5601"},{"type":"tags","id":"5602"},{"type":"tags","id":"12803"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114383"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman at 40 weeks gestation is admitted to hospital for an elective caesarean section. She was diagnosed with gestational hypertension at 26 weeks and gestational diabetes at 28 weeks. Both these conditions have been managed and monitored by the patient and at prenatal appointments. Her current medications are labetalol and pregnancy multivitamins. Recent investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting blood glucose: 9.8 mmol/L (7 - 11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2hr post-prandial glucose: 6.4 mmol/L (7 - 11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 5.1% (\u0026lt;6.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary protein:creatinine ratio: 0.1 (\u0026lt;0.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine dipstick: Leucocytes = 0, RBC = 0, Protein = 0, Ketones = 0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn assessment the patient feels well and denies headaches, visual disturbances, urinary changes or any oedema. Her blood pressure is 110/65 mmHg, pulse 82/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 14/min and SaO2 = 99% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following reflects her ASA (American Society of Anaesthesiologists) physical status?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ASA I","ASA II","ASA III","ASA IV","ASA V"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ASA classification is a system developed by the American Society of Anesthesiologists to evaluate a patient\u0027s pre-anaesthesia medical condition. Although pregnancy is not a disease, it alters the patient\u2019s physiological baseline, which means a pregnant individual is classified as at least\u003Cstrong\u003E ASA II\u003C/strong\u003E rather than \u003Cstrong\u003EASA I\u003C/strong\u003E, which is reserved for completely healthy patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the presence of gestational hypertension or gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) does not automatically shift the classification higher, provided both conditions are well controlled. This patient\u2019s most recent blood glucose levels (BGL) and HbA1c are within normal limits without medication, indicating excellent GDM control, and her blood pressure remains below pre-eclampsia thresholds with no signs of end-organ dysfunction. Given these factors, she would be appropriately categorised as ASA II.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA III\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this classification requires pregnancy-related conditions to be poorly controlled, or requiring significant medical therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA IV\u003C/strong\u003E would be incorrect as the patient has no conditions that are a constant threat to life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA V\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as there is no evidence that the patient would die without surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA useful summary of the ASA classifications as they relate to different patient subsets: \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.asahq.org/standards-and-guidelines/asa-physical-status-classification-system\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.asahq.org/standards-and-guidelines/asa-physical-status-classification-system\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pregnancy, although not a disease, increases ASA classification.","Gestational hypertension and gestational diabetes, when well-controlled, do not elevate ASA classification beyond ASA II."],"references":["Abouleish AE, Leib ML, Cohen NH. ASA provides examples to each ASA physical status class. ASA Monitor 2015; 79:38-9","Daabiss M. American Society of Anaesthesiologists physical status classification. Indian J Anaesth. 2011 Mar;55(2):111-5. doi: 10.4103/0019-5049.79879. PMID: 21712864; PMCID: PMC3106380. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21712864/","Pedrosa E, Silva M, Lobo A, Barbosa J, Mourao J. Is the ASA Classification Universal? Turk J Anaesthesiol Reanim. 2021 Aug;49(4):298-303. doi: 10.5152/TJAR.2021.103. PMID: 35110011; PMCID: PMC10335535. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35110011/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19429"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19429"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1f695ff1-31f2-4a9b-a2e3-698522edd0b1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1f695ff1-31f2-4a9b-a2e3-698522edd0b1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":398}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T09:51:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T09:52:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114383"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}